Bitcoin (BTC) has been trading sideways as some crypto analysts have warned that the digital asset‚Äôs price may become unpredictable in the short-term, according to a new report from OKCoin. The digital currency exchange confirmed that Bitcoin continues to gain institutional support.

BTC‚Äôs recent price action has been ‚Äúrelatively muted‚Äù when compared to the previous week, the report noted. It confirmed that last week Bitcoin recorded a new all-time high. The flagship cryptocurrency is now trading for around $18,300 at the time of writing (having dropped below the $19,000 mark). For the past couple weeks, Bitcoin has mostly been trading in the $18,000 and $19,500 range.

As mentioned in OKCoin‚Äôs crypto market report:

‚ÄúThis consolidation [of the Bitcoin price] has allowed certain altcoins (alternative coins besides BTC) to rally. For instance, Compound‚Äôs COMP has risen considerably in the past week. But large-cap assets like Bitcoin and Ethereum (ETH) have been relatively neutral to negative. Analysts are confident that the overall Bitcoin trajectory is one of growth. Case in point: institutional investors this past week continued to pledge their support for the leading cryptocurrency ‚Äî and seems like Ray Dalio is on board as well.‚Äù

In a separate report, crypto research firm Messari points out that what‚Äôs different today from a few years ago is Bitcoin‚Äôs (BTC) ‚Äúprominence in the macro conversation, and its emergence as a smart money alternative to gold.‚Äù

The extensive report from Messari notes:

Paul Tudor Jones has referred to Bitcoin as ‚Äúthe fastest horse‚Äù;

Stanley Druckenmiller has stated that ‚Äúthe bitcoin bet will probably work better‚Äù than gold;

Billionaire investor Chamath Palihapitiya recommends that ‚Äúeveryone should have 1% of their assets in bitcoin‚Äù;

Wall Street legend Bill Miller ‚Äústrongly recommended‚Äù that investors gain exposure to BTC if they didn‚Äôt yet own the digital asset;

JPMorgan stated that family offices ‚Äúmay be looking at Bitcoin as an alternative to gold‚Äù;

Raoul Pal said that ‚ÄúBitcoin is a supermassive black hole‚Äù;

Messari‚Äôs report also mentioned:

‚ÄúEthereum may have even taken a permanent lead this year versus Bitcoin in terms of economic value transferred on its rails. It‚Äôs hard to ignore five-year-old technologies that process more than $1 trillion in real value transfers per year, a figure that has already eclipsed PayPal‚Äôs. Ethereum has challenges ahead, but its dynamism is undeniable, and it will continue to be the platform to watch in 2021.‚Äù

As confirmed in another report from Coin Metrics, Ethereum (ETH) hash rate has reached a new-all-time high (on December 1, 2020). The ETH hash rate began its sharp rise this past summer, ‚Äúspurred on by the rise of (decentralized finance) DeFi and subsequent rise in ETH transaction fees,‚Äù the report stated. It added that the DeFi mania appears to have ‚Äúcooled off towards the end of September 2020, [and] there were some questions whether ETH‚Äôs hash rate would be able to continue its growth.‚Äù

Coin Metrics further noted:

‚ÄúThe launch of the beginning phases of Ethereum 2.0 and the eventual switch to Proof of Stake raises more questions about how Ethereum‚Äôs Proof of Work system will perform in the interim. Interestingly, ETH‚Äôs hash rate hit a new all-time high the day the ETH 2.0 beacon chain (the first step towards Proof of Stake) went live, and has remained near all-time highs in the days since.‚Äù

